    pearls: ["Orientation is lost in a predictable order: time is lost FIRST, then place, then situation, and person is lost LAST -- progressive loss indicates worsening cognitive function","Delirium is acute onset (hours to days) and fluctuating; dementia is gradual onset (months to years) and progressive -- delirium can be superimposed on dementia","The Confusion Assessment Method (CAM) requires BOTH acute onset with fluctuating course AND inattention, PLUS either disorganized thinking OR altered level of consciousness","Visual hallucinations strongly suggest an organic or medical cause (delirium, substance withdrawal, Lewy body dementia) rather than a primary psychiatric disorder","UTI is the most common cause of acute confusion in elderly patients -- always obtain urinalysis when an elderly patient develops new-onset altered mental status","A GCS drop of 2 or more points from baseline is a significant neurological change that requires immediate assessment and physician notification","Document MSE findings using objective behavioral descriptions (patient is picking at bedsheets and looking at ceiling) rather than interpretive labels (patient is hallucinating)"],
