    pearls: ["MPA is p-ANCA/MPO positive while GPA (Wegener) is c-ANCA/PR3 positive -- knowing this serological distinction is high-yield for NCLEX; MPA does NOT have granulomas or upper airway disease (no saddle nose deformity or sinusitis)","The hallmark renal finding is pauci-immune crescentic glomerulonephritis: hematuria with RBC casts and rapidly rising creatinine -- 'pauci-immune' means little to no immune complex deposits on biopsy (unlike lupus nephritis)","Diffuse alveolar hemorrhage may occur WITHOUT visible hemoptysis in up to one-third of cases -- a dropping hemoglobin with new bilateral infiltrates in an ANCA-positive patient should raise immediate concern for occult DAH","Rituximab infusion reactions are most common during the FIRST infusion -- the nurse must premedicate appropriately, start at a slow rate, and have emergency equipment (epinephrine, oxygen) immediately available","Infection is the leading cause of death during treatment, not the disease itself -- strict infection prevention measures, temperature monitoring, and PJP prophylaxis are critical nursing priorities","Always check urine color at each void and document: tea-colored or cola-colored urine indicates active hematuria and possible disease flare; this is a simple but critical nursing observation","Patients on long-term immunosuppression need education about avoiding live vaccines, recognizing infection symptoms, hand hygiene, and when to seek emergent care -- discharge education is a key nursing role"],
